  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the evolution of anti-money laundering (AML) legislation:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major US legislation\n- Focus on reporting large cash transactions\n- Limited international cooperation\n\n2. 1980s-1990s\n- More comprehensive reporting requirements\n- Enhanced financial institution responsibilities\n- Growing international awareness of money laundering risks\n\n3. Key Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Patriot Act (2001) - Significantly expanded AML regulations\n- Increased scrutiny of financial institutions\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n\n4. Modern Developments\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- International information sharing\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Emphasis on beneficial ownership transparency\n- Advanced technological detection methods\n- Risk-based approach to compliance\n- Broader regulatory scope across different financial sectors\n\n6. Global Collaboration\n- Coordinated international legal frameworks\n- Standardized reporting mechanisms\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Cross-border enforcement mechanisms\n\nThe legislative approach continues evolving to address emerging financial crime complexities.",
